{{Refimprove|date=May 2015}} Kuwait is divided into [[Governorates of Kuwait|six governorates]], in each there are several '''areas''' ({{lang-ar|مناطِق}}).
Areas, due to their small area which does not exceed {{convert|5|km²|0|abbr=on}}, are sometimes called towns. However they are officially translated to ''areas''.<ref>[http://www.kuna.net.kw/ArticlePrintPage.aspx?id=2144192&language=en Kuwait National News Agency]</ref><ref>[http://www.moi.gov.kw/portal/venglish/ShowPage.aspx?newsID=3671 Ministry of Interior]</ref><ref>[http://mew.gov.kw/en/?com=content&act=view&id=55 Ministry of Electricity and Water]</ref> The Arabic word for area, ''[[wiktionary:منطقة|Mantaqa]] منطقة'' can mean both mean ''area'' and ''region''.<ref>[http://dictionary.cambridge.org/us/dictionary/english-arabic/area Cambridge English-Arabic dictionary, ''Area'' translatation]</ref><ref>[http://dictionary.cambridge.org/us/dictionary/english-arabic/region Cambridge English-Arabic dictionary, ''Region'' translatation]</ref>
Each area in Kuwait has an official governmental facility called '''co-op society''' or just '''society''' ({{lang-ar|جمعية}}). For example, in Surra, it's called ''Surra Co-op Society''. Societies are mainly supermarkets that provide foods and produces, and they may take part in maintaining some on the areas' landmarks like parks and schools, but they're not legally obliged to. Societies have elected members who manage them. Only residents of the area can vote for their society membership.
