In [[Greek mythology]], '''Hesperia''' ([[Ancient Greek]]: Ἑσπερια) may refer to the following characters and places:
*[[Asterope (Hesperide)|Hesperia]], one of the [[Hesperides]], in some versions (e.g. [[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Pseudo-Apollodorus]]) the daughter of [[Hesperus]]<ref name="perseus1">{{cite book|author=Apollodorus|author-link=Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|title=Bibliotheca|translator=James George Frazer|translator-link=James George Frazer|publication-place=Cambridge, Massachusetts; London|publisher=Harvard University Press; William Heinemann Ltd.|publication-date=1921}} {{Perseus|Apollod.|2.5.11|}} in {{cite web|title=The Perseus Encyclopedia|access-date=5 May 2017}}{{Perseus|PersEnc.|hesperia|}}</ref> * Hesperia, also called [[Asterope (Greek mythology)|Asterope]], the wife or desired lover of [[Aesacus]] and daughter of the river [[Cebren]]<ref name="perseus2">{{cite book|author=Apollodorus|author-link=Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|title=Bibliotheca|translator=James George Frazer|translator-link=James George Frazer|publication-place=Cambridge, Massachusetts; London|publisher=Harvard University Press; William Heinemann Ltd.|publication-date=1921}} {{Perseus|Apollod.|3.10.1|}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Ovid|author-link=Ovid|title=Metamorphoses|editor=Hugo Magnus|publication-place=Gotha|publisher=Friedrich Perthes|date=1892}}{{Perseus|Ov.|Met|11.769|}}</ref> * Hesperia as "western land" is the ancient Greek name of Italy, also used in Latin epic poetry,<ref name="lsjhesperia">{{LSJ|*(esperi/a|Ἑσπερία|ref}}</ref> in [[Grammatical gender|gender]] either a feminine noun or a neuter plural [[adjective]] used [[Nominalized adjective|substantively]], spelt the same but with different [[definite article]]s, and with the accent shifted from the [[penult]] to the [[antepenult]].<ref name="lsjhesperios">{{LSJ|*(espe/rios|ἑσπέριος|ref}}</ref> This becomes [[Latin]] ''Hesperia'' or ''Hesperius'',<ref name="lshesperus">{{L&S|Hesperia|ref}}</ref><ref name="lshesperius">{{L&S|Hesperius|ref}}</ref> the latter not a distinct nominal form, but simply an adjective used substantively, [[viz.]] [[Vergil|Vergil's]] ''[[Aeneid]]'' VI, 6<ref name="perseus3">{{cite book|author-first=James|author-last=Greenough|author-link=James B. Greenough|title=Bucolics, Aeneid, and Georgics Of Vergil|publication-place=Boston|publisher=Ginn & Co.|publication-date=1900|quote=litus in Hesperium; quaerit pars semina flammae [''Lit.'' A shore in Hesperia [Italy], one of them seeks the seeds of flame.]}}{{Perseus|Verg.|A.|6.1|}}</ref> * Hesperia, the Iberian Peninsula and Northwest Africa, further to the west, used in both Ancient Greek and [[Byzantine]] sources<ref name="lsjhesperia" />
