{{About|the soil type|the locality|Trumao, Chile}} {{Infobox soil |name=Trumao |alternative_name= |type= |type_link= |image= |image_size=250px |image_caption= |horizons= |composition_secondary= |classification_system= |parent_material=primary [[tephra]], or tephra redeposited as [[alluvium]] or by wind |profile=A-(AB)-BA-2C{{refn|name=note 1|group=note|This is an example of a typical profile of the Central Valley. The last horizon may alternatively be R instead of 2C.<ref name=ScGrGe/>}} |code= |process=[[weathering]] |climate=[[Humidity|humid]]<ref name=ScGrGe/> }} '''Trumao''' is the name of a [[soil]] of the [[Andosol]] order found in southern and central [[Chile]]. Trumaos are formed from young [[volcanic ash]], by volcanic ash redeposited by [[aeolian processes]] or by volcanic ash mobilized as [[alluvium]].<ref name=ScGrGe/><ref name="Veblen2007">{{cite book |last=Veblen |first=Thomas T.|author-link=Thomas T. Veblen |editor-last1=Veblen |editor-first1=Thomas T.|editor-last2=Young |editor-first2=Kenneth R.|editor-last3=Orme |editor-first3=Anthony R.|title=Physical Geography of South America |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|date=2007 |pages=219 |chapter=Temperate Forest of the Southern Andean Region |isbn=978-0-19-531341-3}}</ref> Trumaos are characterized by containing the following minerals: [[allophane]], [[imogolite]] plus a series of [[paracrystalline]] and non-crystalline [[clay minerals|clay]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Sanhueza |first=C. |last2=Palma |first2=J.|last3=Valenzuela |first3=P.|last4=Araneda |first4=O. |last5=Calderón |first5=K. |date=September 2011 |title=Evaluación del comportamiento geotécnico de suelos volcánicos chilenos para su uso como material de filtro en la depuración de aguas residuales domésticas |url=http://www.scielo.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0718-915X2011000200007&script=sci_arttext |journal=Revista de la Construcción |publisher=Escuela de Construcción Civil, Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile |volume=10 |issue=2 |pages=66–81 |doi=|language=Spanish |access-date=25 June 2015}}</ref> These soils have high [[porosity]] and low [[bulk density]].<ref name="Veblen2007"/> A more dry and a more humid variety of trumaos exists. The dry variety is known simply as trumao while the humid variety is known as trumao húmedo.<ref name=ScGrGe/>
In terms of [[latitude]] trumaos can be found in the Andes from 33° S to 43° S, in the [[Chilean Central Valley|Central Valley]] from 38° S to 43° S and in the eastern slopes of the [[Chilean Coast Range]] from 39° S to 43° S.<ref name=ScGrGe>{{cite book |last=Schlatter |first=Juan |last2=Grez|first2=Renato|last3=Gerding|first3=Víctor |date=2003 |title=Manual para el reconocimiento de suelos |url= |location=[[Valdivia]] |publisher=[[Universidad Austral de Chile]] |pages=94–95 |language=Spanish|isbn=956-7105-25-1}}</ref>
